That is correct. The two-place aircraft made the concept of  &quot;two-man
control&quot; a lot easier to implement in fighters. Prior to that time
there were a lot of single seat fighters with only the pilot in charge
of the weapon after launch. Getting to launch, however, took a lot of
cooperating people doing their jobs.

The nuclear consent switch required that both cockpits operate the
switches to get a weapon armed and released.

There was also the PAL, a locking device that was implemented during
the Eisenhower administration. Initially it was an electronic panel
with four rotary dials to set a four-digit code to  unlock the weapon.
In the mid-sixties PAL was upgraded to six digit code with limited
trials before deactivation. (All of this was &quot;long ago, far away&quot; and
published in the unclassified manuals--i.e., public domain.)

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
